The effective number of codons (ENC) is used to measure deviation from expected random codon usage of BVDV and is independent of hypotheses involving natural selection [5]. The ENC values range from 20 to 61. The larger the codon preference in a gene is, the smaller the ENC value is. In an extremely biased gene where only one codon is used for each amino acid, this value would be 20, and if all codons were used equally, it would be 61 [28, 31]. The formulas for ENC are as follows:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
